 specific sentencing range. However, no source provides sentencing specifics or prosecutor/defense guidance on expected sentence length, making the precise mechanism inferential rather than confirmed. The sustained pattern of 8 sequential downward moves over ~44 minutes suggests a news-driven repricing, not noise.\",\n  \"macro_or_idiosyncratic\": \"IDIOSYNCRATIC\",\n  \"macro_reasoning\": \"This is entirely specific to the Weinstein retrial verdict. No broader legal, political, or macroeconomic event is implicated. The concurrent moves are all on Weinstein sentencing range markets, confirming this is case-specific.\",\n  \"expected_duration\": \"SUSTAINED\",\n  \"duration_reasoning\": \"A verdict is a discrete, irreversible event. The market is now pricing a post-conviction world with a mixed record. Unless sentencing guidelines or prosecutorial statements clarify the likely range, this repricing should hold until a sentencing date or new legal developments.\",\n  \"trading_implication\": \"A trader should assess whether the mixed verdict makes a sub-10-year sentence more likely (e.g., fewer convictions reducing guidelines range) or an above-20-year sentence possible. If the top charge carries a mandatory minimum above 10 years, the sell-off may be overdone. Conversely, if the acquittals reduce the guidelines range below 10 years, further downside exists. Monitor sentencing hearing scheduling and defense/prosecution statements on expected range.\",\n  \"alternative_explanations\": [\n    \"Automated market maker or liquidity algorithm rebalancing across correlated Weinstein sentencing range markets without a specific news trigger\",\n    \"A single informed trader with legal expertise selling down multiple correlated markets based on their read of the mixed verdict's sentencing implications\",\n    \"Mistrial on key charges (not just acquittal) could mean retrial risk, further delaying or complicating sentencing \u2014 traders may be pricing in procedural uncertain